===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|sweren|lang=enm}}, {{term|swerien|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|swerian||to swear, take an oath of office|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*swarjaną||to speak, swear}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*swer-||to speak, talk}}. Cognate with {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|swarre||to swear|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|frs|-}} {{term|swera||to swear|lang=frs}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|zweren||to swear, vow|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|swören||to swear|lang=nds}}, {{term|sweren|lang=nds}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|schwören||to swear|lang=de}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|sværge|lang=da}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|svära||to swear|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|sverja||to swear|lang=is}}. Also cognate to {{etyl|sq|-}} {{term|var||to hang, consider, to depend from|lang=sq}} through Proto-Indo-European.

